{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17641589","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17641589"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:28:41+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:28:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17888"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17888","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17888"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.27,0.68,0.05,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10602"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78482"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10602","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10602"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17888"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63845"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"5102"},{"type":"tags","id":"10069"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24708"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24710"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78482","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78482"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following enzymes is directly affected by glucagon to promote fatty acid oxidation in the liver during fasting?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Carnitine translocase","Carnitine-palmitoyl transferase-I","Acetyl-CoA carboxylase","Acylcarnitine translocase","Carnitine-palmitoyl transferase-II"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EGlucagon promotes fatty acid oxidation in the liver by inhibiting \u003Cstrong\u003Eacetyl-CoA carboxylase\u003C/strong\u003E. This inhibition decreases the production of malonyl-CoA, a molecule that normally inhibits carnitine-palmitoyl transferase-I. With lower malonyl-CoA levels, carnitine-palmitoyl transferase-I activity increases, facilitating the transport of fatty acids into the mitochondria for oxidation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECarnitine translocase\u003C/strong\u003E - This enzyme is involved in the transport of acylcarnitine across the mitochondrial membrane but is not directly regulated by glucagon\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECarnitine-palmitoyl transferase-I\u003C/strong\u003E - While its activity is increased indirectly by glucagon, it is not the enzyme directly affected\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcylcarnitine translocase\u003C/strong\u003E - Similar to carnitine translocase, it is involved in transport but not directly regulated by glucagon\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECarnitine-palmitoyl transferase-II\u003C/strong\u003E - This enzyme is involved in the conversion of acylcarnitine back to acyl-CoA within the mitochondria and is not directly regulated by glucagon\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBy inhibiting acetyl-CoA carboxylase, glucagon effectively enhances the liver\u0027s capacity to oxidise fatty acids during fasting, providing energy in the absence of dietary glucose.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Glucagon promotes fatty acid oxidation in the liver by inhibiting acetyl-CoA carboxylase.","Inhibition of acetyl-CoA carboxylase decreases malonyl-CoA levels, relieving inhibition on carnitine-palmitoyl transferase-I and enhancing fatty acid oxidation."]